This award was originally issued as 1039043, and reissued as 1313897 after the principal investigator changed home institutions.



The Great Lakes (GL) are a vital freshwater resource with chronic water quality problems. Climate-change-induced extreme events affect the region?s ecosystems and ecosystem services, with impacts on social and economic well-being. Despite mounting evidence of the severity of these issues, knowledge about how the climate, ecological, and social systems interact as coupled systems is limited. The re-eutrophication of Lake Erie illustrates the complex interactions among natural and human systems, and points to the challenge of managing this resource effectively and adaptively. The viability and economic success of the region are both affected by, and an important determinant of, water quality in the GL basin.  In this project, we proposed to examine the potential impacts and feedbacks among climate, the economic and governance structures that influence human behavior and organizations, the hydrologic system controlling water quality, and the ecological response to the sum total of the changes caused by these interacting systems. 



We asked: What are the possible effects of climate-change-induced extreme events on water quality and ecology in the GL system, and what management strategies would be effective to address these changes?



Specifically, we examined the expected impact of climate-change-related extreme events on nutrient loading to the GL, under land-use patterns altered as a result of agricultural and demographic responses to climate change, and their impacts on ecological responses in the lakes.  The ecological focus was on Lake Erie, especially the lake?s western basin, which is particularly sensitive to climate drivers, to take advantage of extensive ongoing data collection and research efforts already being carried out by the research team.  We also explored the development of governance and management systems that are robust and support adaptation in this context.  We examined the physical processes that affect present-day and future precipitation in the region, including understanding the interactions between the land, lake and atmosphere and its role in the intensity, duration and timing of precipitation events.



The overall scientific goals of this project were (1) to enhance understanding of expected impacts of climate-change-induced extreme events on water quality and ecology, with the GL, and Lake Erie specifically, as a case study; and (2) to develop a framework for integrating human and biogeochemical controls on water quality, ecology and climate that transcends and integrates across social, economic, ecological, hydrological, and geosciences perspectives. 



The broader impacts, outreach, and education components of the study were centered around (i) promoting teaching, training and learning through integration of climatological and ecological research into K-12 science education, (ii) broadening participation of underrepresented groups through a pilot program with the Ypsilanti New Tech High School, (iii) developing educational and professional development resources to enhance scientific and technological understanding, and (iv) delivering benefits to society through the scientific impact of the conducted research and direct involvement of watershed councils and government agencies in the project. 



At its completion, the project had advanced the state-of-the-science in a number of areas, with contributions broadly falling under the following themes:

Improved understanding of processes controlling nutrient (phosphorus and nitrogen) inputs into the Great Lakes in general, and Lake Erie in particular, including the influence of land management (including agricultural practices), meteorology, anthropogenic nutrient addition to soils, land use, and climate change;
Improved understanding of nutrient (phosphorus and nitrogen) limitations on harmful algal blooms in Lake Erie;
Improved understanding of circulation and stratification in Lake Erie and their role in the formation of harmful algal blooms and hypoxic dead zones;
Improvements in approaches for tracking harmful algal blooms in Lake Erie, including innovations in both in situ and remote sensing capabilities;
The development of models for identifying controlling processing for, and projecting the magnitude of, annual Lake Erie HABs and hypoxia;
The documentation and analysis of extreme water quality events in Lake Erie, including the 2011 record HAB and the 2012 record hypoxic dead zone;
Improved understanding of the interactions between the impacts of human action at regional (e.g. land management, agricultural) and global (e.g. climate change) scales on eutrophication and associated water quality impacts;
Improved understanding of regional meteorological and climate feedbacks and surface-atmosphere interactions on precipitation;
Improved approaches for the evaluation and bias correction of climate models;
The development of strategy for effectively engaging with stakeholders for identifying improved approaches to nutrient management.




The project has thus far yielded over forty publications in scientific journals, including in Science, Nature, and the Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences. The project directly contributed to the research and teaching skills of over 20 undergraduate students, 15 graduate students, and 12 postdoctoral researchers.

